==Old English==
===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*dō-'', from Indo-European ''*dhe-'' ‘make, do, place’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''duā'', Old Saxon ''dōn'' (Dutch [[doen]]), Old High German [[tuon]] (German [[tun]]); and, outside the Germanic languages, with Greek [[τιθέναι]], Latin ''-dere'' ([[abdere]], [[condere]]), Old Irish [[dorat]] (Irish [[déan]]), Slavic ''*děti'' (Old Church Slavonic [[дѣло]], Russian [[деть]]).

